                    <item_0
                        jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                        sling:resourceType="core/franklin/components/block/v1/block/item"
                        model="text-container-text"
                        modelFields="[text]"
                        name="Text Container Text"
                        text="&lt;p>For many children, a rainstorm is nothing special.&lt;/p>&lt;p>Maybe it’s an opportunity to spend the afternoon inside watching movies or playing games. An excuse to debut a new raincoat at school; a chance to splash in puddles.&lt;/p>&lt;p>For Fredrick Bailey, a rainstorm was life.&lt;/p>&lt;p>Bailey, 31, recalls his childhood in LaGrange, Georgia, living in a home without electricity or running water. With both parents suffering from drug addiction and his father often gone, a 12-year-old Bailey placed a bucket on the front porch and prayed for rain – precious water he needed to wash his clothes. One winter night, scrubbing his jeans with rainwater and a bar of soap, Bailey had enough.&lt;/p>&lt;p>“I told myself, I convinced myself, life is better than this,” Bailey says. “And I wanted to experience that better life.”&lt;/p>&lt;p>Today, Bailey is truly experiencing that better life. He credits an intervention from national education nonprofit &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.communitiesinschools.org/&quot; title=&quot; Communities In Schools &quot;>Communities In Schools&lt;/a> (CIS) as the catalyst both academically and on a personal level, that enabled him to change the trajectory of his future.&lt;/p>"/>
                </block_1>
